Question 7 [6 Points]

Write a shell script patterns.sh that reads a text file and:
• Writes words containing ONLY vowels into vowels.txt
• Writes words containing ONLY consonants into consonants.txt
• Writes words containing both vowels and consonants but starting with a consonant into mixed.txt, Case should be ignored while checking patterns.

===============================================
===================================================

patterns.sh

#!/bin/bash

# Normalize input: convert non‑letters to newlines, lowercase everything
words=$(tr -cs 'A-Za-z' '\n' < input.txt | tr 'A-Z' 'a-z')

# Empty output files
> vowels.txt
> consonants.txt
> mixed.txt

for w in $words
do
    # Word contains only vowels
    if echo "$w" | grep -Eq '^[aeiou]+$'; then
        echo "$w" >> vowels.txt

    # Word contains only consonants
    elif echo "$w" | grep -Eq '^[bcdfghjklmnpqrstvwxyz]+$'; then
        echo "$w" >> consonants.txt

    # Word starts with consonant AND contains both vowels and consonants
    elif echo "$w" | grep -Eq '^[bcdfghjklmnpqrstvwxyz]' \
         && echo "$w" | grep -Eq '[aeiou]' \
         && echo "$w" | grep -Eq '[bcdfghjklmnpqrstvwxyz]'; then
        echo "$w" >> mixed.txt
    fi
done

======================================
========================================
Normalize text
tr -cs 'A-Za-z' '\n'
===================================
Breaks text into clean words.

 Lowercase everything
Makes pattern matching case‑insensitive.

 Only vowels
^[aeiou]+$

========================================
Only consonants
^[bcdfghjklmnpqrstvwxyz]+$

